# Slide 21

- Enhancement using Histogram processing
- Includes two techniques:

a-Histogram equalization.

b-Histogram matching.

---
# Slide 22

- A- Histogram equalization
- The histogram equalization transform is the integral of the original histogram function (i/p image histogram) multiplied by scaling factor L-1/N  where:
                     L…..brightness values
                     N…Total number of pixel

---
# Slide 23

- B- Histogram equalization algorithm
- 1-Assign i/p number of pixels associated to each i/p brightness values.
2-Compute the cumulative number of pixels 
(unscaled values).
3-Multiply each unscaled value with the scaling factor   L-1/N to obtain the new scaled value.
4-Assign a nearest available brightness values to the new scaled value.
5-Then draw the histogram of enhanced o/p image (brightness values against nearest available brightness values).

# Slide 25

- Some arithmetic logic operation performed on images
- A-Image subtraction:
The difference between two images f(x,y) & h(x,y) expressed as:
g(x,y)=f(x,y)-h(x,y)
B-Image averaging:
-Consider a noisy image g(x,y) formed by addition of noise (x,y) to original image f(x,y):
g(x,y)=f(x,y)+ (x,y)
-The objective here is to reduce the noise content by adding a set of noisy images{gi(x,y)}

# Slide 26

- Enhancement using spatial filters
- A-Smoothing filters:
Are used to reduce or remove noise from an image.

B-Sharpening filters:
Are used for highlighting edges in an image.

# Slide 27

- Smoothing filters:
- 1-Median filter (non-linear filter) (order statistics  filters):
Algorithm: Suppose the window size is 33 and suppose this window is centered at (i, j)
sort the gray level values of the nine pixels in pix(i,j) that are in the window according to gray level.
Assign pix(i,j) the middle gray level value appearing in the sort.
Replace the pix(i,j) with the new median value.
Repeat the process over all pixels in image.

# Slide 41

- Smoothing frequency domain filters
- Edges and other sharp transitions (such as noise) 
in the gray levels of an image contribute 
significantly to the high frequency content of its 
fourier transform . hence smoothing (blurring)  is 
achieved in the frequency domain by attenuating a specified range of high frequency components in the transform of a given image .
